1
00:00:02,586 --> 00:00:04,254
And why are we chasing it?

2
00:00:04,379 --> 00:00:08,008
It's mauve and dangerous, and about
30 seconds from the centre of London.

3
00:00:08,091 --> 00:00:10,302
Excuse me, there's this thing
that I need to find.

4
00:00:10,427 --> 00:00:12,054
Would've fallen from the sky.

5
00:00:12,137 --> 00:00:16,141
Nancy, the thing I'm looking for,
you know what I'm talking about, don't you?

6
00:00:16,892 --> 00:00:18,060
(ROSE SCREAMING)

7
00:00:18,810 --> 00:00:20,395
I've got you, you're fine.

8
00:00:20,479 --> 00:00:21,939
-Hello.
-Hello.

9
00:00:22,064 --> 00:00:24,566
Jack Harkness, I've been hearing
all about you on the way over.

10
00:00:24,650 --> 00:00:29,446
It's 1941, the height of the London Blitz,
and something else has fallen on London.

11
00:00:29,613 --> 00:00:31,573
He said it was a warship,
he stole it.

12
00:00:31,657 --> 00:00:34,493
Parked it somewhere,
somewhere a bomb's going to fall on it,

13
00:00:34,618 --> 00:00:36,286
unless we make him an offer.

14
00:00:36,411 --> 00:00:40,666
It's a con. I was conning you.
That's what I am. I'm a con man.

15
00:00:41,458 --> 00:00:43,627
Mummy.

16
00:00:43,961 --> 00:00:46,004
There's something chasing you
and the other kids.

17
00:00:46,129 --> 00:00:48,966
Mummy. Mummy!

18
00:00:49,091 --> 00:00:50,801
You mustn't let him touch you.

19
00:00:50,926 --> 00:00:53,220
-What happens if he touches me?
-He makes you like him.

20
00:00:53,303 --> 00:00:57,432
Right, everybody out, across the back garden,
under the fence. Now, go, move!

21
00:00:58,475 --> 00:01:01,728
You'll find them everywhere,
in every bed in every ward.

22
00:01:01,812 --> 00:01:03,146
Hundreds of them.

23
00:01:03,272 --> 00:01:06,441
They've all got the same injuries,
scarring on the back of the hand,

24
00:01:06,525 --> 00:01:08,652
and the gas mask seems to be
fused to the flesh.

25
00:01:08,777 --> 00:01:11,822
-What was the cause of death?
-They're not dead.

26
00:01:11,947 --> 00:01:13,657
Are you my mummy?

27
00:01:13,782 --> 00:01:16,034
It's me Nancy!

28
00:01:16,159 --> 00:01:18,870
-Don't let them touch you.
-What happens if they touch us?

29
00:01:18,996 --> 00:01:20,706
You're looking at it.

30
00:01:20,998 --> 00:01:24,001
ALL: Mummy. Mummy...

31
00:01:27,004 --> 00:01:28,505
Go to your room.

32
00:01:33,552 --> 00:01:35,220
Go to your room.

33
00:01:39,558 --> 00:01:43,186
I mean it, I'm very, very angry with you.

34
00:01:43,353 --> 00:01:45,522
I'm very, very cross.

35
00:01:47,691 --> 00:01:51,153
Go to your room!

36
00:02:13,216 --> 00:02:15,385
I'm really glad that worked.

37
00:02:15,510 --> 00:02:17,679
Those would have been
terrible last words.

38
00:02:18,680 --> 00:02:20,724
(DOCTOR WHO THEME MUSIC)

39
00:03:02,474 --> 00:03:03,767
Jamie.

40
00:03:26,289 --> 00:03:29,000
-Why are they all wearing gas masks?
-They're not.

41
00:03:29,126 --> 00:03:31,086
Those masks are flesh and bone.

42
00:03:31,169 --> 00:03:34,756
-How was your con supposed to work?
-Simple enough, really.

43
00:03:34,840 --> 00:03:36,758
Find some harmless piece of space junk,

44
00:03:36,842 --> 00:03:39,136
let the nearest Time Agent
track it back to Earth,

45
00:03:39,261 --> 00:03:41,346
convince him it's valuable
and name a price.

46
00:03:41,471 --> 00:03:43,598
When he's put 50% upfront...oops!

47
00:03:43,682 --> 00:03:46,560
German bomb falls on it,
destroys it forever.

48
00:03:46,643 --> 00:03:50,939
He never gets to see what he's paid for,
never knows he's been had.

49
00:03:51,022 --> 00:03:54,317
I buy him a drink with his own money
and we discuss dumb luck.

50
00:03:54,443 --> 00:03:57,821
-The perfect self-cleaning con.
-Yeah. Perfect.

51
00:03:57,988 --> 00:03:59,823
The London Blitz is great
for self-cleaners.

52
00:03:59,990 --> 00:04:02,659
Pompeii's nice if you want to make
a vacation of it, though.

53
00:04:02,784 --> 00:04:05,537
But you've got to set your alarm
for Volcano Day.

54
00:04:05,662 --> 00:04:07,205
(JACK LAUGHING)

55
00:04:09,666 --> 00:04:12,627
-Getting a hint of disapproval.
-Take a look around the room.

56
00:04:12,711 --> 00:04:15,046
This is what your piece of
harmless space junk did.

57
00:04:15,172 --> 00:04:18,967
It was a burnt-out medical transporter,
it was empty.

58
00:04:19,050 --> 00:04:20,469
Rose.

59
00:04:20,552 --> 00:04:22,721
-Are we getting out of here?
-We're going upstairs.

60
00:04:22,846 --> 00:04:25,724
I programmed the flight computer
so it wouldn't land on anything living.

61
00:04:25,807 --> 00:04:26,892
I harmed no one!

62
00:04:27,184 --> 00:04:30,061
I don't know what's happening here
but I had nothing to do with it.

63
00:04:30,145 --> 00:04:31,313
I'll tell you what's happening.

64
00:04:31,563 --> 00:04:34,858
You forgot to set your alarm clock.
It's Volcano Day.

65
00:04:35,025 --> 00:04:36,151
(SIREN WAILING)

66
00:04:36,234 --> 00:04:38,737
-What's that?
-The all clear.

67
00:04:39,821 --> 00:04:41,364
I wish.

68
00:04:53,251 --> 00:04:54,711
(NANCY EXCLAIMS)

69
00:04:58,924 --> 00:05:00,759
I thought you were Jamie.

70
00:05:05,263 --> 00:05:06,932
-Dad! Dad!
-Ruddy kids!

71
00:05:07,057 --> 00:05:08,934
-Get off of me!
-Give us a hand.

72
00:05:09,059 --> 00:05:13,230
-Get your hands off me now!
-You! Get in!

73
00:05:13,355 --> 00:05:16,733
Get her in there.
She's nicked!

74
00:05:17,567 --> 00:05:19,402
-Mr Spock?
-Doctor.

75
00:05:19,903 --> 00:05:21,738
Have you got a blaster?

76
00:05:24,741 --> 00:05:26,243
Sure.

77
00:05:28,745 --> 00:05:31,081
The night your space junk landed,
someone was hurt.

78
00:05:31,248 --> 00:05:33,250
-This is where they were taken.
-What happened?

79
00:05:33,375 --> 00:05:35,710
Let's find out. Get it open.

80
00:05:36,753 --> 00:05:39,256
-What's up with your sonic screwdriver?
-Nothing.

81
00:05:42,634 --> 00:05:46,179
Sonic blaster, 51st century.
Weapon factories of Villengard.

82
00:05:46,263 --> 00:05:47,722
-You've been to the factories?
-Once.

83
00:05:47,806 --> 00:05:51,351
They're gone now, destroyed.
Main reactor went critical, vaporised the lot.

84
00:05:51,476 --> 00:05:53,311
Like I said. Once.

85
00:05:53,436 --> 00:05:57,274
There's a banana grove there now.
I like bananas. Bananas are good.

86
00:05:59,192 --> 00:06:01,695
-Nice blast pattern.
-Digital.

87
00:06:01,778 --> 00:06:04,614
-Squareness gun? I like it.
-Yeah.

88
00:06:13,582 --> 00:06:16,668
-What do you think?
-Something got out of here.

89
00:06:16,793 --> 00:06:18,336
Yeah. And?

90
00:06:19,254 --> 00:06:22,340
Something powerful. Angry.

91
00:06:23,300 --> 00:06:24,801
Powerful and angry.

92
00:06:44,613 --> 00:06:45,989
A child?

93
00:06:46,489 --> 00:06:50,160
-I suppose this explains "mummy"”.
-How could a child do this?

94
00:06:51,328 --> 00:06:55,040
-Do you know where you are?
-Are you my mummy?

95
00:06:56,166 --> 00:06:59,002
Are you aware of
what's around you?

96
00:06:59,127 --> 00:07:01,838
Can you...see?

97
00:07:02,005 --> 00:07:03,882
Are you my mummy?

98
00:07:04,007 --> 00:07:07,969
-What do you want? Do you know...
-I want my mummy!

99
00:07:08,720 --> 00:07:11,222
Are you my mummy?
I want my mummy.

100
00:07:12,349 --> 00:07:14,184
Are you my mummy?

101
00:07:15,226 --> 00:07:17,437
Are you my mummy?

102
00:07:17,520 --> 00:07:20,315
Mummy? Mummy?

103
00:07:22,817 --> 00:07:25,362
-Doctor, I've heard this voice before.
-Me, too.

104
00:07:25,487 --> 00:07:26,655
Mummy?

105
00:07:26,738 --> 00:07:29,407
Always "are you my mummy?"
Like he doesn't know.

106
00:07:29,532 --> 00:07:30,825
Mummy.

107
00:07:30,909 --> 00:07:32,243
Why doesn't he know?

108
00:07:32,369 --> 00:07:35,372
Are you there, Mummy? Mummy?

109
00:07:40,585 --> 00:07:42,921
The police are on their way.

110
00:07:43,546 --> 00:07:46,633
I pay for
the food on this table.

111
00:07:46,716 --> 00:07:50,720
The sweat on my brow, that food is.
The sweat on my brow.

112
00:07:51,763 --> 00:07:54,641
Anything else you'd like?
I've got a whole house here.

113
00:07:54,724 --> 00:07:57,394
Anything else you'd like to
help yourself to?

114
00:07:58,269 --> 00:07:59,562
Yeah.

115
00:07:59,938 --> 00:08:01,773
I'd like some
wire cutters, please.

116
00:08:01,898 --> 00:08:04,234
Something that can cut through
barbed wire.

117
00:08:04,359 --> 00:08:08,029
Oh, and a torch.
Don't look like that, Mr Lloyd.

118
00:08:08,113 --> 00:08:12,367
I know you got plenty of tools in here.
I been watching this house for ages.

119
00:08:12,951 --> 00:08:15,578
And I'd like another look round
your kitchen cupboards.

120
00:08:15,704 --> 00:08:19,207
I was in a hurry the first time.
I want to see if there's anything I missed.

121
00:08:19,290 --> 00:08:20,417
The food on this table...

122
00:08:20,542 --> 00:08:23,086
It's an awful lot of food,
isn't it, Mr Lloyd?

123
00:08:23,211 --> 00:08:25,588
A lot more than on
anyone else's table.

124
00:08:25,755 --> 00:08:27,132
Half this street thinks

125
00:08:27,215 --> 00:08:30,427
your missus must be messing about
with Mr Haverstock, the butcher.

126
00:08:30,760 --> 00:08:32,762
But she's not, is she?

127
00:08:33,555 --> 00:08:37,934
You are.
Wire cutters. Torch. Food.

128
00:08:38,101 --> 00:08:41,396
And I'd like to use your bathroom
before I leave, please.

129
00:08:41,479 --> 00:08:44,899
Oh, look! There's
the sweat on your brow.

130
00:08:51,489 --> 00:08:54,451
Mummy? Please, Mummy. Mummy?

131
00:08:54,576 --> 00:08:55,785
Doctor?

132
00:08:55,952 --> 00:08:57,996
-Can you sense it?
-Sense what?

133
00:08:58,121 --> 00:09:01,124
Coming out of the walls.
Can you feel it?

134
00:09:01,833 --> 00:09:04,919
Funny little human brains.
How do you get around in those things?

135
00:09:05,003 --> 00:09:07,005
When he's stressed,
he likes to insult species.

136
00:09:07,130 --> 00:09:09,716
-Rose, I'm thinking!
-He cuts himself shaving.

137
00:09:09,799 --> 00:09:12,218
He does half an hour on life-forms
he's cleverer than.

138
00:09:12,302 --> 00:09:15,013
There are these children.
Living rough round the bomb sites.

139
00:09:15,138 --> 00:09:17,265
They come out during air raids,
looking for food.

140
00:09:17,348 --> 00:09:18,558
Mummy, please.

141
00:09:18,641 --> 00:09:21,644
Suppose they were there when this thing,
whatever it was, landed.

142
00:09:21,770 --> 00:09:24,522
-It was a med-ship, it was harmless.
-You keep saying. Harmless.

143
00:09:24,647 --> 00:09:27,984
-Suppose one was affected. Altered.
-Altered how?

144
00:09:28,109 --> 00:09:29,652
I'm here!

145
00:09:29,778 --> 00:09:33,156
It's afraid, terribly afraid and powerful.

146
00:09:33,323 --> 00:09:35,366
It doesn't know it yet.
But it will do.

147
00:09:35,492 --> 00:09:36,993
(FAINT WHIRRING)

148
00:09:37,118 --> 00:09:39,954
It's got the power of a god
and I just sent it to its room.

149
00:09:40,038 --> 00:09:41,790
(WHIRRING)

150
00:09:41,873 --> 00:09:42,999
Doctor.

151
00:09:43,166 --> 00:09:44,793
I'm here! Can't you see me?

152
00:09:44,876 --> 00:09:46,711
What's that noise?

153
00:09:48,171 --> 00:09:51,674
End of the tape.
It ran out about 30 seconds ago.

154
00:09:52,467 --> 00:09:55,345
I'm here now!
Can't you see me?

155
00:09:55,553 --> 00:09:59,182
I sent it to its room.
This is its room.

156
00:10:02,852 --> 00:10:04,646
Are you my mummy?

157
00:10:07,357 --> 00:10:08,650
Mummy?

158
00:10:09,150 --> 00:10:10,485
Doctor?

159
00:10:10,693 --> 00:10:15,323
Okay, on my signal
make for the door.

160
00:10:15,406 --> 00:10:17,283
-Mummy?
-Now!

161
00:10:17,367 --> 00:10:18,743
Mummy?

162
00:10:20,495 --> 00:10:23,164
-Go, now, don't drop the banana!
-Why not?

163
00:10:23,248 --> 00:10:25,375
Good source of potassium.

164
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:27,210
Give me that.

165
00:10:27,335 --> 00:10:30,588
Mummy? I want my mummy.

166
00:10:33,049 --> 00:10:36,052
Digital rewind. Nice switch.

167
00:10:36,511 --> 00:10:39,389
It's from the groves of Villengard,
thought it was appropriate.

168
00:10:39,514 --> 00:10:42,559
There's really a banana grove in Villengard?
And you did that?

169
00:10:42,725 --> 00:10:44,227
Bananas are good.

170
00:10:44,394 --> 00:10:46,271
-Doctor!
-Come on!

171
00:10:53,361 --> 00:10:56,614
ALL: Mummy! Mummy!

172
00:11:03,288 --> 00:11:05,331
It's keeping us here
till it can get at us.

173
00:11:05,415 --> 00:11:07,292
-It's controlling them?
-It is them.

174
00:11:07,417 --> 00:11:09,460
It's every living thing in this hospital.

175
00:11:09,586 --> 00:11:11,629
Okay. This can function
as a sonic blaster,

176
00:11:11,754 --> 00:11:14,924
a sonic cannon and
it's a triple-enfolded sonic disruptor.

177
00:11:15,091 --> 00:11:18,136
-Doc, what you got?
-I've got a sonic... Never mind.

178
00:11:18,261 --> 00:11:20,597
-What?
-It's sonic, okay? Let's leave it at that.

179
00:11:20,763 --> 00:11:22,348
Disruptor? Cannon? What?

180
00:11:22,432 --> 00:11:24,976
It's sonic, totally sonic.
I am soniced up.

181
00:11:25,101 --> 00:11:28,062
-A sonic what?
-Screwdriver!

182
00:11:32,650 --> 00:11:34,110
Going down.

183
00:11:38,907 --> 00:11:40,575
Doctor, are you okay?

184
00:11:40,658 --> 00:11:43,286
-Could've used a warning.
-The gratitude.

185
00:11:43,411 --> 00:11:45,496
-Who has a sonic screwdriver?
-I do.

186
00:11:45,622 --> 00:11:46,915
Lights?

187
00:11:46,998 --> 00:11:49,959
Who looks at a screwdriver and thinks,
"Ooh, this could be more sonic?"

188
00:11:50,126 --> 00:11:52,754
-You've never been bored?
-There's got to be a light switch.

189
00:11:52,837 --> 00:11:56,007
Never had a long night?
Never had a lot of cabinets to put up?

190
00:11:56,257 --> 00:11:58,009
-Mummy.
-Mummy.

191
00:11:58,134 --> 00:11:59,344
Door.

192
00:12:03,598 --> 00:12:04,849
-Damn it!
-Mummy?

193
00:12:04,974 --> 00:12:07,477
It's the special features,
they really drain the battery.

194
00:12:07,602 --> 00:12:08,978
The battery?

195
00:12:10,647 --> 00:12:12,065
It's so lame.

196
00:12:12,148 --> 00:12:15,818
I was going to send for another one
but somebody's got to blow up the factory.

197
00:12:15,944 --> 00:12:17,946
I know. First day I met him,
he blew my job up.

198
00:12:18,029 --> 00:12:19,614
That's practically
how he communicates.

199
00:12:19,697 --> 00:12:21,366
Okay, that door
should hold it for a bit.

200
00:12:21,491 --> 00:12:24,369
-The door? The wall didn't stop it.
-It's got to find us first!

201
00:12:24,494 --> 00:12:26,704
Come on, we're not done yet.
Assets.

202
00:12:26,829 --> 00:12:29,999
I've got a banana and, in a pinch,
you could put up some shelves.

203
00:12:30,166 --> 00:12:32,627
-Window?
-Barred. Sheer drop. Seven storeys.

204
00:12:32,710 --> 00:12:33,962
And no other exits.

205
00:12:34,045 --> 00:12:37,507
The assets conversation went in a flash,
didn't it?

206
00:12:38,341 --> 00:12:40,468
-Where'd you pick this one up, then?
-Doctor.

207
00:12:40,551 --> 00:12:43,805
She was hanging from a barrage balloon,
I had an invisible spaceship.

208
00:12:43,888 --> 00:12:45,723
I never stood a chance.

209
00:12:45,848 --> 00:12:47,600
Okay. One,
we've got to get out of here.

210
00:12:47,684 --> 00:12:50,353
Two, we can't get out of here.
Have I missed anything?

211
00:12:51,354 --> 00:12:54,357
Yeah. Jack just disappeared.

212
00:13:04,534 --> 00:13:07,537
I thought as much.
What are all of you doing here?

213
00:13:07,662 --> 00:13:09,622
Different house
every night I told you.

214
00:13:09,706 --> 00:13:12,292
We thought you were dead.
Or you'd run off.

215
00:13:12,375 --> 00:13:14,752
I didn't. I knew
you'd come back for us.

216
00:13:20,174 --> 00:13:22,010
Found that old thing in the junk.

217
00:13:22,093 --> 00:13:24,679
-Thinks he's can write now.
-Writing a letter to me dad.

218
00:13:24,762 --> 00:13:27,598
You don't even know where your dad is.
How you gonna send it?

219
00:13:27,724 --> 00:13:30,893
-I don't know, stick it in an envelope.
-You can't even read or write.

220
00:13:31,060 --> 00:13:32,854
I don't need to,
I've got a machine.

221
00:13:32,937 --> 00:13:35,231
Will you stop
making that noise?

222
00:13:39,610 --> 00:13:41,070
I'm sorry, Jim.

223
00:13:42,196 --> 00:13:45,742
On you go, you write a letter
to your dad if you want to.

224
00:13:51,456 --> 00:13:53,458
I know we should
have went somewhere else

225
00:13:53,583 --> 00:13:55,918
but we need you, see,
for the thinking.

226
00:13:56,419 --> 00:13:58,421
What if I wasn't here?

227
00:13:58,546 --> 00:14:00,923
What if one night
I didn't come back for you?

228
00:14:01,049 --> 00:14:03,760
There's a war on,
people go out.

229
00:14:03,885 --> 00:14:06,137
They don't always come back.
It happens.

230
00:14:07,263 --> 00:14:08,765
What would you do then?

231
00:14:15,772 --> 00:14:17,982
They're wire cutters.

232
00:14:18,107 --> 00:14:20,109
I need you to
think about that.

233
00:14:20,234 --> 00:14:24,322
-Someone's got to look after this lot.
-Why? Are you going somewhere?

234
00:14:26,449 --> 00:14:29,786
The bomb site.
The one at the railway station.

235
00:14:29,994 --> 00:14:32,121
-Why?
-The child.

236
00:14:34,123 --> 00:14:35,750
That's where he was killed.

237
00:14:35,833 --> 00:14:38,544
That's where it all started.
And I'm gonna find out how.

238
00:14:38,628 --> 00:14:40,880
-He'll get you.
-And then he'll come for us.

239
00:14:40,963 --> 00:14:45,093
-He always comes for us.
-No, Ernie, he doesn't.

240
00:14:46,135 --> 00:14:48,304
He always comes after me.

241
00:14:48,971 --> 00:14:52,975
There are things I haven't told you.
Things I can't tell you.

242
00:14:54,310 --> 00:14:58,648
As long as you're with me,
you're in danger.

243
00:14:58,773 --> 00:15:01,442
Even right now. Sitting here.
You're in danger because of me.

244
00:15:01,526 --> 00:15:03,736
You're the one
that keeps us safe.

245
00:15:03,820 --> 00:15:06,781
You think so, Ernie?
Then answer this.

246
00:15:08,699 --> 00:15:11,327
Jim is sitting
there right next to you.

247
00:15:13,454 --> 00:15:14,831
So who's typing?

248
00:15:34,684 --> 00:15:35,977
Is he coming?

249
00:15:36,060 --> 00:15:40,189
Ernie, as long as you're with me,
he's always coming.

250
00:15:42,358 --> 00:15:44,819
Plenty of greens.
And chew your food.

251
00:15:55,538 --> 00:15:57,373
Okay, so he's
vanished into thin air.

252
00:15:57,498 --> 00:16:00,251
Why is it always the great-looking ones
who do that?

253
00:16:00,376 --> 00:16:04,881
-I'm making an effort not to be insulted.
-I mean, men.

254
00:16:05,214 --> 00:16:07,508
Okay, thanks, that really helped.

255
00:16:07,717 --> 00:16:09,677
Rose? Doctor? Can you hear me?

256
00:16:09,760 --> 00:16:10,928
(STATIC)

257
00:16:11,053 --> 00:16:12,847
Back on my ship.

258
00:16:12,930 --> 00:16:16,058
Used the emergency teleport.
Sorry I couldn't take you.

259
00:16:16,184 --> 00:16:18,895
It's security-keyed
to my molecular structure.

260
00:16:19,061 --> 00:16:20,688
I'm working on it,
hang in there.

261
00:16:20,771 --> 00:16:22,190
How are you speaking to us?

262
00:16:22,273 --> 00:16:24,609
Om-Com. I can call anything
with a speaker grill.

263
00:16:24,734 --> 00:16:26,903
-Now there's a coincidence.
-What is?

264
00:16:27,028 --> 00:16:29,739
-The child can Om-Com, too.
-He can?

265
00:16:29,906 --> 00:16:32,617
Anything with a speaker grill.
Even the Tardis phone.

266
00:16:32,742 --> 00:16:34,577
What, you mean
the child can phone us?

267
00:16:34,702 --> 00:16:39,248
And I can hear you.
Coming to find you.

268
00:16:39,373 --> 00:16:42,084
Coming to find you.

269
00:16:42,210 --> 00:16:44,128
-Doctor, can you hear that?
-Loud and clear.

270
00:16:44,253 --> 00:16:46,631
I'll try to block out the signal.
Least I can do.

271
00:16:46,756 --> 00:16:48,466
Coming to find you, Mummy.

272
00:16:48,591 --> 00:16:50,593
Remember this one, Rose?

273
00:16:51,427 --> 00:16:54,096
(MOONLIGHT SERENADE PLAYING)

274
00:16:56,974 --> 00:16:58,768
Our song.

275
00:17:46,774 --> 00:17:47,900
What you doing?

276
00:17:47,984 --> 00:17:51,779
Trying to set up a resonation pattern
in the concrete, loosen the bars.

277
00:17:51,862 --> 00:17:56,117
-Do you think he's coming back?
-Wouldn't bet my life.

278
00:17:56,200 --> 00:17:57,493
Why don't you trust him?

279
00:17:57,618 --> 00:17:59,954
-Why do you?
-Saved my life.

280
00:18:00,037 --> 00:18:02,665
Bloke-wise, that's up there with flossing.

281
00:18:06,210 --> 00:18:10,840
I trust him because he's like you.
Except with dating and dancing.

282
00:18:14,802 --> 00:18:16,387
-What?
-You just assume I'm...

283
00:18:16,512 --> 00:18:19,849
-What?
-You just assume I don't dance.

284
00:18:20,141 --> 00:18:22,643
What? Are you
telling me you do dance?

285
00:18:22,727 --> 00:18:24,937
900 years old, me.
I've been around a bit.

286
00:18:25,021 --> 00:18:27,315
I think you can assume at some point
I've danced.

287
00:18:27,398 --> 00:18:29,233
-You?
-Problem?

288
00:18:29,358 --> 00:18:32,320
Doesn't the universe implode
or something if you dance?

289
00:18:32,403 --> 00:18:35,156
Well, I've got the moves
but I wouldn't want to boast.

290
00:18:45,333 --> 00:18:47,710
(STILL PLAYING MOONLIGHT SERENADE)

291
00:18:50,046 --> 00:18:53,007
You've got the moves?
Show me your moves.

292
00:18:53,758 --> 00:18:56,427
Rose, I'm trying to resonate concrete.

293
00:18:56,552 --> 00:18:59,388
Jack will be back. He'll get us out.
So come on.

294
00:18:59,513 --> 00:19:02,391
The world doesn't end
because the Doctor dances.

295
00:19:11,609 --> 00:19:14,403
-Barrage balloon?
-What?

296
00:19:15,029 --> 00:19:16,906
You were hanging
from a barrage balloon.

297
00:19:17,031 --> 00:19:20,284
Oh. Yeah.
About two minutes after you left me.

298
00:19:20,409 --> 00:19:23,162
Thousands of feet above London,
middle of a German air raid,

299
00:19:23,245 --> 00:19:24,914
Union Jack all over my chest.

300
00:19:25,039 --> 00:19:26,540
I've travelled with a lot of people

301
00:19:26,624 --> 00:19:29,377
but you're setting new records
for jeopardy friendly.

302
00:19:30,086 --> 00:19:32,463
Is this you dancing?
Because I've got notes.

303
00:19:32,588 --> 00:19:35,424
Hanging from a rope,
thousands of feet above London.

304
00:19:35,591 --> 00:19:37,510
Not a cut, not a bruise.

305
00:19:37,593 --> 00:19:39,553
Yeah, I know.
Captain Jack fixed me up.

306
00:19:39,637 --> 00:19:41,389
We're calling him Captain Jack now,
are we?

307
00:19:41,472 --> 00:19:44,100
His name's Jack
and he's a captain.

308
00:19:44,225 --> 00:19:47,561
-He's not really a captain, Rose.
-Do you know what I think?

309
00:19:48,312 --> 00:19:51,232
I think you're
experiencing captain-envy.

310
00:19:52,608 --> 00:19:54,860
You will find your feet
at the end of your legs.

311
00:19:54,944 --> 00:19:56,362
You may care to move them.

312
00:19:56,445 --> 00:19:58,406
If ever he was a captain,
he's been defrocked.

313
00:19:58,489 --> 00:20:01,826
-Yeah? Shame I missed that.
-Actually, I quit.

314
00:20:01,951 --> 00:20:03,619
Nobody takes my frock.

315
00:20:04,954 --> 00:20:07,540
Most people notice
when they've been teleported.

316
00:20:07,623 --> 00:20:09,583
You guys are so sweet.

317
00:20:09,667 --> 00:20:11,001
Sorry about the delay.

318
00:20:11,127 --> 00:20:14,171
Had to take the Nav-Com
off-line to override the teleport security.

319
00:20:14,296 --> 00:20:16,757
You can spend 10 minutes
overriding your own protocols.

320
00:20:16,841 --> 00:20:18,926
Maybe you should remember
whose ship it is.

321
00:20:19,260 --> 00:20:21,846
I do. She was gorgeous.

322
00:20:21,971 --> 00:20:24,849
Like I told her,
be back in five minutes.

323
00:20:25,975 --> 00:20:29,937
-This is a Chula ship.
-Yeah, just like that medical transporter.

324
00:20:30,020 --> 00:20:31,939
Only this one is dangerous.

325
00:20:33,274 --> 00:20:35,609
They're what fixed up my hands up.
Jack called them...

326
00:20:35,693 --> 00:20:37,653
-Nanobots? Nanogenes?
-Nanogenes, yeah.

327
00:20:37,778 --> 00:20:40,990
Subatomic robots.
There are millions of them in here. See?

328
00:20:41,157 --> 00:20:44,076
Burned my hand on the console
when we landed. All better now.

329
00:20:44,160 --> 00:20:46,036
They activate
when the bulkhead's sealed.

330
00:20:46,162 --> 00:20:48,664
Check you out for damage,
fix any physical flaws.

331
00:20:50,666 --> 00:20:53,627
Take us to the crash site.
I need to see your space junk.

332
00:20:53,711 --> 00:20:57,673
Soon as I get the Nav-Com back online.
Make yourself comfortable.

333
00:20:57,798 --> 00:21:01,010
Carry on with whatever it was
you were doing.

334
00:21:01,135 --> 00:21:04,013
-We were talking about dancing.
-It didn't look like talking.

335
00:21:04,138 --> 00:21:06,056
Didn't feel like dancing.

336
00:21:23,532 --> 00:21:25,493
Halt! Don't move!

337
00:21:29,246 --> 00:21:32,833
So, you used to be a Time Agent
and now you're trying to con them?

338
00:21:32,917 --> 00:21:35,503
If it makes me sound any better,
it's not for the money.

339
00:21:35,586 --> 00:21:37,171
For what?

340
00:21:37,254 --> 00:21:39,965
Woke up one morning
when I was still working for them,

341
00:21:40,049 --> 00:21:42,384
found they'd stolen two years
of my memories.

342
00:21:42,510 --> 00:21:45,596
-I'd like them back.
-They stole your memories?

343
00:21:45,721 --> 00:21:48,432
Two years of my life.
No idea what I did.

344
00:21:49,266 --> 00:21:53,938
Your friend over there doesn't trust me.
And for all I know, he's right not to.

345
00:21:54,939 --> 00:21:58,943
Okay. We're good to go.
The crash site?

346
00:22:00,903 --> 00:22:04,365
-As you were. You feeling any better?
-Just a touch, sir.

347
00:22:04,782 --> 00:22:07,243
Chain her up where Jenkins
can keep an eye on her.

348
00:22:07,368 --> 00:22:09,703
No. Not in here. Not with him.

349
00:22:10,079 --> 00:22:12,832
You shouldn't have broken in here
if you didn't want to stay.

350
00:22:12,915 --> 00:22:15,209
You don't understand.
Not with him.

351
00:22:15,292 --> 00:22:17,628
This is
a restricted area, miss.

352
00:22:17,753 --> 00:22:19,630
You can just sit
here for a bit.

353
00:22:19,755 --> 00:22:22,132
We're going to have to ask you
a few questions.

354
00:22:22,258 --> 00:22:23,592
Found these, sir.

355
00:22:24,635 --> 00:22:28,264
Very professional,
a little bit too professional.

356
00:22:28,389 --> 00:22:30,474
Didn't just drop in by accident then,
did you?

357
00:22:30,599 --> 00:22:32,268
My little brother died here.

358
00:22:32,393 --> 00:22:34,520
I wanted to find out what killed him.

359
00:22:34,603 --> 00:22:37,106
Take the men, check the fence
for any other breaches.

360
00:22:37,231 --> 00:22:40,025
And search the area,
she may not have come here alone.

361
00:22:40,109 --> 00:22:41,777
-Yes, sir!
-Please.

362
00:22:41,902 --> 00:22:43,863
Listen, you can't leave me here.

363
00:22:43,946 --> 00:22:46,282
-Watch her, Jenkins.
-Yes, Mummy.

364
00:22:48,117 --> 00:22:50,119
-Jenkins?
-Sorry.

365
00:22:50,744 --> 00:22:53,080
Sir, I don't know
what's the matter with me.

366
00:22:53,247 --> 00:22:57,501
Look, lock me up, fine, but not here.
Please, anywhere but here.

367
00:22:59,461 --> 00:23:02,840
You'll be all right, miss.
I'm just a little...

368
00:23:03,757 --> 00:23:06,135
Just a little...

369
00:23:06,260 --> 00:23:07,636
What's the matter with you?

370
00:23:07,761 --> 00:23:11,098
-Please, let me go.
-Why would I do that?

371
00:23:11,181 --> 00:23:13,392
Because you've got a scar
on the back of your hand.

372
00:23:13,475 --> 00:23:16,020
Yes, but I don't see
what that's got to do with anything.

373
00:23:16,145 --> 00:23:17,521
You feel like
you're gonna be sick.

374
00:23:17,646 --> 00:23:19,982
Like something's
forcing its way up your throat.

375
00:23:20,149 --> 00:23:22,693
I know because
I've seen it before.

376
00:23:22,860 --> 00:23:26,822
-What's happening to me?
-In a minute you won't be you anymore.

377
00:23:27,114 --> 00:23:28,949
You won't even remember you.

378
00:23:29,033 --> 00:23:32,494
And unless you let me go,
it's going to happen to me, too.

379
00:23:32,620 --> 00:23:34,788
-Please.
-What are you talking about?

380
00:23:34,872 --> 00:23:37,291
-What's your mother's name?
-Matilda.

381
00:23:37,374 --> 00:23:39,001
-You got a wife?
-Yes.

382
00:23:39,126 --> 00:23:40,586
Wife's name?

383
00:23:40,669 --> 00:23:43,964
You got kids?
What's your name?

384
00:23:45,341 --> 00:23:49,595
Please, let me go.
It's too late for you. I'm sorry.

385
00:23:49,678 --> 00:23:51,805
But please let me go.

386
00:23:53,349 --> 00:23:55,225
What...

387
00:23:55,684 --> 00:23:58,520
Mummy!

388
00:24:11,492 --> 00:24:12,868
There it is.

389
00:24:13,535 --> 00:24:16,580
They've got Algy on duty.
Must be important.

390
00:24:16,705 --> 00:24:18,415
We've got to get past him.

391
00:24:18,540 --> 00:24:21,877
Are the words "distract the guard”
heading in my general direction?

392
00:24:22,002 --> 00:24:24,129
I don't think that'd
be such a good idea.

393
00:24:24,213 --> 00:24:26,048
Don't worry, I can handle it.

394
00:24:26,173 --> 00:24:28,884
I've got to know Algy quite well
since I've been in town.

395
00:24:29,009 --> 00:24:31,345
Trust me, you're not his type.

396
00:24:32,054 --> 00:24:33,514
I'll distract him.

397
00:24:35,849 --> 00:24:37,226
Don't wait up.

398
00:24:40,771 --> 00:24:42,898
Relax.
He's a 51st century guy.

399
00:24:43,023 --> 00:24:45,776
He's just a bit more flexible
when it comes to dancing.

400
00:24:46,402 --> 00:24:47,861
How flexible?

401
00:24:47,945 --> 00:24:50,739
By his time,
you lot are spread out across half the galaxy.

402
00:24:50,864 --> 00:24:54,201
-Meaning?
-So many species, so little time.

403
00:24:54,284 --> 00:24:56,453
What, that's what we do
when we get out there?

404
00:24:56,578 --> 00:24:59,540
That's our mission?
We seek new life and...

405
00:25:00,958 --> 00:25:02,251
Dance.

406
00:25:07,589 --> 00:25:09,758
Hey, tiger. How's it hanging?

407
00:25:13,262 --> 00:25:15,431
-Mummy?
-Algy, old sport, it's me.

408
00:25:16,598 --> 00:25:19,059
-Mummy?
-It's me, Jack.

409
00:25:19,268 --> 00:25:20,477
Jack?

410
00:25:22,479 --> 00:25:24,732
Are you my mummy?

411
00:25:40,581 --> 00:25:43,459
Stay back! You men, stay away.

412
00:25:48,422 --> 00:25:51,091
The effect's becoming airborne,
accelerating.

413
00:25:51,175 --> 00:25:53,302
-What's keeping us safe?
-Nothing.

414
00:25:53,677 --> 00:25:56,055
-Here they come again.
-All we need.

415
00:25:56,138 --> 00:25:57,806
(SIRENS WAILING)

416
00:25:57,931 --> 00:26:00,350
Didn't you say a bomb
was gonna land here?

417
00:26:00,476 --> 00:26:01,894
Never mind about that.

418
00:26:01,977 --> 00:26:04,271
If the contaminant's airborne now,
there's hours left.

419
00:26:04,354 --> 00:26:05,564
-Till what?
-Till nothing.

420
00:26:05,647 --> 00:26:07,733
Forever.
For the entire human race.

421
00:26:07,816 --> 00:26:09,443
And can anyone
else hear singing?

422
00:26:09,526 --> 00:26:11,070
# ...the tree tops

423
00:26:11,153 --> 00:26:14,656
# When the wind blows
the cradle will rock

424
00:26:15,657 --> 00:26:19,036
# When the bow breaks
the cradle will fall

425
00:26:19,620 --> 00:26:22,831
# Down will come
baby cradle and all

426
00:26:27,503 --> 00:26:31,173
# Rock-a-bye baby
on the tree tops

427
00:26:32,049 --> 00:26:35,177
# When the wind blows
the cradle will rock #

428
00:26:45,729 --> 00:26:47,856
You see? Just an ambulance.

429
00:26:48,190 --> 00:26:49,775
That's an ambulance?

430
00:26:49,858 --> 00:26:53,695
It's hard to explain.
It's from another world.

431
00:26:53,904 --> 00:26:56,240
-They've been trying to get in.
-Of course they have.

432
00:26:56,365 --> 00:26:59,451
They think they've got their hands on
Hitler's latest secret weapon.

433
00:26:59,535 --> 00:27:02,204
-What are you doing?
-The sooner you see this thing's empty,

434
00:27:02,329 --> 00:27:04,540
the sooner you'll know
I had nothing to do with it.

435
00:27:07,668 --> 00:27:08,877
Didn't happen last time.

436
00:27:09,002 --> 00:27:11,713
It hadn't crashed last time.
There'll be emergency protocols.

437
00:27:11,839 --> 00:27:13,715
Doctor, what is that?

438
00:27:19,221 --> 00:27:20,389
Mummy.

439
00:27:32,526 --> 00:27:33,735
Doctor!

440
00:27:36,238 --> 00:27:38,073
-Captain, secure those gates.
-Why?

441
00:27:38,198 --> 00:27:40,617
Just do it!

442
00:27:40,742 --> 00:27:42,327
Nancy, how did you get in here?

443
00:27:42,411 --> 00:27:44,371
-I cut the wire.
-Show Rose.

444
00:27:44,454 --> 00:27:46,707
Setting 2,428-D.

445
00:27:46,790 --> 00:27:49,418
-What?
-Reattaches barbed wire. Go!

446
00:28:08,312 --> 00:28:10,772
Who are you?
Who are any of you?

447
00:28:11,440 --> 00:28:13,108
Never believe me if I told you.

448
00:28:13,233 --> 00:28:15,903
You just told me that was
an ambulance from another world.

449
00:28:15,986 --> 00:28:19,323
There are people running round
with gas masks calling for their mummies

450
00:28:19,448 --> 00:28:22,075
and the sky's full of Germans
dropping bombs on me.

451
00:28:22,159 --> 00:28:25,621
Tell me, do you think
there's anything left I couldn't believe?

452
00:28:27,247 --> 00:28:29,708
We're time travellers.
From the future.

453
00:28:29,791 --> 00:28:33,337
-Mad, you are!
-We have a time travel machine.

454
00:28:33,462 --> 00:28:37,591
It's not that. All right,
you got a time travel machine.

455
00:28:37,966 --> 00:28:40,594
I'll believe you.
Believe anything, me.

456
00:28:42,346 --> 00:28:44,264
But what future?

457
00:28:48,143 --> 00:28:50,771
Nancy, this isn't the end.

458
00:28:50,854 --> 00:28:54,024
I know how it looks,
it's not the end of the world or anything.

459
00:28:54,149 --> 00:28:56,944
How can you say that?
Look at it.

460
00:28:57,027 --> 00:28:59,947
Listen to me.
I was born in this city.

461
00:29:00,030 --> 00:29:02,741
I'm from here,
in like 50 years' time.

462
00:29:02,824 --> 00:29:05,118
-From here?
-I'm a Londoner.

463
00:29:05,827 --> 00:29:09,248
-From your future.
-But...

464
00:29:09,331 --> 00:29:11,750
-But you're not...
-What?

465
00:29:11,833 --> 00:29:14,086
-German?
-Nancy.

466
00:29:14,169 --> 00:29:17,172
The Germans don't come here.
They don't win.

467
00:29:17,965 --> 00:29:21,385
Don't tell anyone I told you so.
But you know what?

468
00:29:22,052 --> 00:29:24,638
-You win.
-We win?

469
00:29:26,682 --> 00:29:27,975
Come on.

470
00:29:29,810 --> 00:29:31,520
It's empty. Look at it.

471
00:29:31,645 --> 00:29:34,356
What do you expect
in a Chula medical transporter?

472
00:29:34,481 --> 00:29:36,358
Bandages? Cough drops?

473
00:29:36,483 --> 00:29:38,694
-Rose?
-I don't know.

474
00:29:39,027 --> 00:29:41,446
-Yes, you do.
-Nanogenes!

475
00:29:41,530 --> 00:29:43,699
It wasn't empty, Captain.

476
00:29:44,032 --> 00:29:47,369
There was enough nanogenes in there
to rebuild a species.

477
00:29:48,078 --> 00:29:50,664
-Oh, God.
-Getting it now, are we?

478
00:29:50,747 --> 00:29:52,916
When the ship crashes,
the nanogenes escape.

479
00:29:53,041 --> 00:29:54,584
Billions upon billions of them.

480
00:29:54,710 --> 00:29:57,713
Ready to fix all the cuts and bruises
in the whole world.

481
00:29:57,838 --> 00:30:00,424
But what they find first is a dead child.

482
00:30:00,549 --> 00:30:03,719
Probably killed earlier that night.
And wearing a gas mask.

483
00:30:03,844 --> 00:30:06,513
And they brought him back to life?
They can do that?

484
00:30:06,596 --> 00:30:09,474
What's life? Life's easy.
A quirk of matter.

485
00:30:09,558 --> 00:30:13,020
Nature's way of keeping meat fresh.
Nothing to a nanogene.

486
00:30:13,103 --> 00:30:14,396
One problem, though.

487
00:30:14,521 --> 00:30:17,065
These nanogenes,
they're not like the ones on your ship.

488
00:30:17,190 --> 00:30:19,318
This lot have never seen
a human being before.

489
00:30:19,401 --> 00:30:21,987
Don't know what a human being's
supposed to look like.

490
00:30:22,070 --> 00:30:25,866
All they've got to go on is one little body,
and there's not a lot left.

491
00:30:25,949 --> 00:30:27,117
But they carry right on.

492
00:30:27,242 --> 00:30:29,703
They do what they're programmed to,
they patch it up.

493
00:30:29,786 --> 00:30:32,873
Can't tell what's gas mask and what's skull,
but they do their best.

494
00:30:32,956 --> 00:30:35,625
And then off they fly, off they go,
work to be done.

495
00:30:35,751 --> 00:30:38,879
"Cause you see, now they think
they know what people should look like.

496
00:30:38,962 --> 00:30:41,798
And it's time to fix all the rest.
And they won't ever stop.

497
00:30:41,923 --> 00:30:43,467
They won't ever stop.

498
00:30:43,592 --> 00:30:46,303
The entire human race
is gonna be torn down

499
00:30:46,428 --> 00:30:50,432
and rebuilt in the form of one terrified child
looking for its mother.

500
00:30:50,557 --> 00:30:53,560
-And nothing in the world can stop it!
-I didn't know.

501
00:31:09,451 --> 00:31:10,702
Mummy.

502
00:31:10,786 --> 00:31:11,995
Rose?

503
00:31:17,292 --> 00:31:20,462
Mummy. Mummy...

504
00:31:26,927 --> 00:31:28,970
It's bringing the gas mask people here,
isn't it?

505
00:31:29,096 --> 00:31:33,183
The ship thinks it's under attack.
It's calling up the troops. Standard protocol.

506
00:31:33,308 --> 00:31:35,352
But the gas mask people aren't troops!

507
00:31:35,477 --> 00:31:37,604
They are now.
This is a battlefield ambulance.

508
00:31:37,687 --> 00:31:41,149
The nanogenes don't just fix you up,
they get you ready for the front line.

509
00:31:41,316 --> 00:31:44,569
-Equip you, program you.
-That's why the child's so strong?

510
00:31:44,653 --> 00:31:46,238
Why it could do that phoning thing?

511
00:31:46,321 --> 00:31:49,157
It's a fully equipped Chula warrior, yes.

512
00:31:49,282 --> 00:31:52,285
All that weapons tech in the hands
of an hysterical four-year-old

513
00:31:52,369 --> 00:31:55,831
looking for his mummy
and now there's an army of them.

514
00:31:55,997 --> 00:31:58,208
Mummy. Mummy.

515
00:32:00,043 --> 00:32:01,503
Why don't they attack?

516
00:32:01,628 --> 00:32:04,714
Good little soldiers.
Waiting for their commander.

517
00:32:04,840 --> 00:32:06,883
The child?

518
00:32:07,008 --> 00:32:08,510
-Jamie.
-What?

519
00:32:09,177 --> 00:32:11,221
Not the child. Jamie.

520
00:32:11,680 --> 00:32:14,224
-So how long until the bomb falls?
-Any second.

521
00:32:14,349 --> 00:32:17,727
What's the matter, Captain?
Bit close to the volcano for you?

522
00:32:17,853 --> 00:32:19,646
-He's just a little boy.
-I know.

523
00:32:19,729 --> 00:32:22,899
-He's just a boy who wants his mummy.
-I know.

524
00:32:24,568 --> 00:32:25,944
There isn't a little boy born

525
00:32:26,027 --> 00:32:28,989
who wouldn't tear the world apart
to save his mummy.

526
00:32:29,656 --> 00:32:33,160
-And this little boy can.
-So what are we gonna do?

527
00:32:33,869 --> 00:32:35,412
I don't know.

528
00:32:36,913 --> 00:32:39,583
-It's my fault.
-No.

529
00:32:39,708 --> 00:32:41,918
-It is. It's all my fault.
-How can it be your...

530
00:32:42,043 --> 00:32:45,172
Mummy. Mummy.

531
00:32:46,590 --> 00:32:48,550
-Mummy
-Mummy!

532
00:32:48,717 --> 00:32:50,260
Mummy!

533
00:32:57,017 --> 00:32:58,727
Nancy, what age are you?

534
00:33:00,562 --> 00:33:03,607
207217 Older than you look, yes?

535
00:33:06,109 --> 00:33:08,904
Doctor, that bomb, we've got seconds.

536
00:33:10,113 --> 00:33:12,616
-You can teleport us out.
-Not you guys.

537
00:33:12,741 --> 00:33:14,409
The Nav-Com's back online.

538
00:33:14,534 --> 00:33:16,661
Gonna take too long
to override the protocols.

539
00:33:16,745 --> 00:33:19,456
So it's Volcano Day.
Do what you've got to do.

540
00:33:19,581 --> 00:33:20,790
Jack?

541
00:33:26,087 --> 00:33:28,965
How old were you five years ago?
157167

542
00:33:29,591 --> 00:33:31,927
Old enough to give birth, anyway.

543
00:33:33,803 --> 00:33:36,223
He's not your brother, is he?

544
00:33:37,974 --> 00:33:40,435
A teenage single mother in 1941.

545
00:33:41,394 --> 00:33:43,772
So you hid. You lied.

546
00:33:44,814 --> 00:33:46,775
You even lied to him.

547
00:33:51,613 --> 00:33:53,281
Are you my mummy?

548
00:33:54,908 --> 00:33:56,952
He's gonna keep asking, Nancy.

549
00:33:57,077 --> 00:33:59,454
-He's never gonna stop.
-Mummy.

550
00:33:59,955 --> 00:34:01,289
Tell him.

551
00:34:04,167 --> 00:34:08,755
Nancy, the future of the human race
is in your hands.

552
00:34:08,838 --> 00:34:10,966
Trust me and tell him.

553
00:34:13,843 --> 00:34:16,429
Are you my mummy?

554
00:34:18,807 --> 00:34:20,642
Are you my mummy?

555
00:34:22,269 --> 00:34:23,853
Are you my mummy?

556
00:34:23,979 --> 00:34:28,650
-Yes, I am your mummy.
-Mummy?

557
00:34:30,485 --> 00:34:34,155
-I'm here.
-Are you my mummy?

558
00:34:38,118 --> 00:34:39,619
I'm here.

559
00:34:39,703 --> 00:34:42,414
-Are you my mummy?
-Yes.

560
00:34:42,497 --> 00:34:43,873
Are you my mummy?

561
00:34:43,999 --> 00:34:46,710
He doesn't understand,
there's not enough of him left.

562
00:34:49,170 --> 00:34:54,009
I am your mummy.
I will always be your mummy.

563
00:34:55,635 --> 00:34:57,137
I'm so sorry.

564
00:34:58,888 --> 00:35:01,683
I'm so, so sorry.

565
00:35:04,394 --> 00:35:06,146
What's happening?

566
00:35:08,982 --> 00:35:10,900
-Doctor, it's changing her, we should...
-Shh!

567
00:35:12,152 --> 00:35:13,862
Come on. Please!

568
00:35:14,654 --> 00:35:18,199
Come on, you clever little nanogenes.
Figure it out.

569
00:35:19,534 --> 00:35:22,495
The mother, she's the mother.

570
00:35:22,579 --> 00:35:24,998
It's got to be enough information.
Figure it out.

571
00:35:25,081 --> 00:35:27,083
-What' s happening?
-See? I.

572
00:35:28,084 --> 00:35:30,211
Recognising the same DNA.

573
00:35:38,219 --> 00:35:40,930
Come on.
Give me a day like this.

574
00:35:41,765 --> 00:35:43,516
Give me this one.

575
00:35:55,028 --> 00:35:59,032
Welcome back!
20 years to pop music, you're gonna love it.

576
00:35:59,407 --> 00:36:00,575
What happened?

577
00:36:00,700 --> 00:36:04,162
The nanogenes recognised
the superior information. The parent DNA.

578
00:36:04,245 --> 00:36:06,915
They didn't change you
because you changed them.

579
00:36:08,291 --> 00:36:10,710
-Mother knows best.
-Jamie.

580
00:36:11,961 --> 00:36:14,005
-Doctor, that bomb.
-Taken care of it.

581
00:36:14,089 --> 00:36:15,757
-How?
-Psychology.

582
00:36:27,936 --> 00:36:30,146
-Doctor!
-Good lad.

583
00:36:30,397 --> 00:36:35,402
The bomb's already started detonation.
I've put it in stasis, but it won't last!

584
00:36:35,485 --> 00:36:37,320
Change of plan!
Don't need the bomb.

585
00:36:37,445 --> 00:36:39,197
Can you get rid of it,
safely as you can?

586
00:36:39,280 --> 00:36:41,408
-Rose?
-Yeah?

587
00:36:41,658 --> 00:36:42,992
Goodbye.

588
00:36:46,788 --> 00:36:49,582
By the way. Love the T-shirt!

589
00:37:10,979 --> 00:37:13,648
-What are you doing?
-Software patch.

590
00:37:13,857 --> 00:37:17,485
Gonna email the upgrade.
You want moves, Rose.

591
00:37:18,319 --> 00:37:19,696
I'll give you moves.

592
00:37:30,290 --> 00:37:34,002
Everybody lives, Rose.
Just this once!

593
00:37:34,711 --> 00:37:36,504
Everybody lives!

594
00:37:42,635 --> 00:37:45,638
Dr Constantine,
who never left his patients.

595
00:37:45,722 --> 00:37:47,515
Back on your feet,
constant doctor.

596
00:37:47,640 --> 00:37:49,726
World doesn't want to get by
without you just yet

597
00:37:49,851 --> 00:37:51,853
and I don't blame it one bit.

598
00:37:52,020 --> 00:37:54,856
These are your patients.
All better now.

599
00:37:55,148 --> 00:37:57,150
Yes, so it seems.

600
00:37:57,901 --> 00:38:00,987
They also seem to be standing around
in a disused railway station.

601
00:38:01,070 --> 00:38:02,864
Is there any particular reason for that?

602
00:38:02,989 --> 00:38:04,491
Yeah, well, you know, cutbacks.

603
00:38:04,574 --> 00:38:06,534
Listen, whatever was wrong
with them in the past

604
00:38:06,701 --> 00:38:08,661
you're probably gonna find
that they're cured.

605
00:38:08,745 --> 00:38:10,371
Just tell them what a great doctor you are,

606
00:38:10,497 --> 00:38:12,582
don't make a big thing of it.
Okay?

607
00:38:14,709 --> 00:38:16,586
Dr Constantine.

608
00:38:17,420 --> 00:38:19,839
Mrs Harcourt!
How much better you're looking!

609
00:38:19,923 --> 00:38:21,841
My leg's grown back.

610
00:38:22,383 --> 00:38:26,346
When I come to the hospital,
I had one leg.

611
00:38:26,429 --> 00:38:30,225
Well, there is a war on,
is it possible you miscounted?

612
00:38:30,558 --> 00:38:34,145
Right, you lot. Lots to do.
Beat the Germans, save the world.

613
00:38:34,229 --> 00:38:36,356
Don't forget
the welfare state!

614
00:38:38,233 --> 00:38:41,152
Setting this to self-destruct,
soon as everybody's clear.

615
00:38:41,236 --> 00:38:42,862
History says there
was an explosion here.

616
00:38:42,946 --> 00:38:46,199
-Who am I to argue with history?
-Usually, the first in line.

617
00:38:49,244 --> 00:38:50,870
The nanogenes will clean up the mess

618
00:38:50,954 --> 00:38:53,331
and switch themselves off,
'cause I just told them to.

619
00:38:53,414 --> 00:38:56,376
Nancy and Jamie will go to
Dr Constantine for help, ditto.

620
00:38:56,459 --> 00:38:59,212
All in all, all things considered. Fantastic!

621
00:38:59,295 --> 00:39:01,506
Look at you beaming away
like you're Father Christmas.

622
00:39:01,589 --> 00:39:03,800
Who says I'm not?
Red bicycle when you were 12.

623
00:39:04,425 --> 00:39:06,886
-What?
-And everybody lives, Rose.

624
00:39:06,970 --> 00:39:09,681
Everybody lives.
I need more days like this!

625
00:39:09,764 --> 00:39:12,809
-Doctor.
-Go on, ask me anything. I'm on fire.

626
00:39:13,101 --> 00:39:14,435
What about Jack?

627
00:39:15,770 --> 00:39:17,564
Why did he say goodbye?

628
00:39:26,322 --> 00:39:29,742
Okay, computer,
how long can we keep the bomb in stasis?

629
00:39:29,826 --> 00:39:32,453
Stasis decaying at 90% cycle.

630
00:39:32,579 --> 00:39:36,249
-Detonation in three minutes.
-Can we jettison it?

631
00:39:36,332 --> 00:39:40,086
Any attempt to jettison the device
will precipitate detonation.

632
00:39:40,169 --> 00:39:44,507
-100% probability.
-We could stick it in an escape pod?

633
00:39:44,632 --> 00:39:46,718
There is no escape pod on board.

634
00:39:46,801 --> 00:39:49,345
Okay, see the flaw in that.
I'll get in the escape pod.

635
00:39:49,470 --> 00:39:51,848
There is no escape pod on board.

636
00:39:51,973 --> 00:39:54,434
-Did you check everywhere?
-Affirmative.

637
00:39:54,517 --> 00:39:56,853
-Under the sink?
-Affirmative.

638
00:40:00,273 --> 00:40:01,482
Okay.

639
00:40:02,025 --> 00:40:04,569
Out of 100,
exactly how dead am I?

640
00:40:04,652 --> 00:40:08,281
Termination of Captain Jack Harkness
in under two minutes.

641
00:40:08,364 --> 00:40:10,825
100% probability.

642
00:40:12,452 --> 00:40:14,704
Lovely. Thanks.

643
00:40:15,788 --> 00:40:18,374
-Good to know the numbers.
-You're welcome.

644
00:40:19,125 --> 00:40:21,336
Okay, then!

645
00:40:21,461 --> 00:40:25,298
Think we'd better initiate
emergency protocol 417.

646
00:40:25,381 --> 00:40:26,883
Affirmative.

647
00:40:36,684 --> 00:40:39,687
A little too much vermouth.
See if I come here again.

648
00:40:43,024 --> 00:40:44,525
Funny thing.

649
00:40:45,360 --> 00:40:47,737
Last time I was sentenced to death

650
00:40:47,862 --> 00:40:51,032
I ordered four hyper-vodkas
for my breakfast.

651
00:40:52,492 --> 00:40:54,911
All a bit of a blur after that.

652
00:40:55,203 --> 00:40:57,872
Woke up in bed
with both my executioners.

653
00:40:58,706 --> 00:41:01,376
Lovely couple.
They stayed in touch.

654
00:41:01,876 --> 00:41:04,712
Can't say that
about most executioners.

655
00:41:08,007 --> 00:41:09,258
Anyway.

656
00:41:11,177 --> 00:41:13,680
Thanks for everything, computer.

657
00:41:14,263 --> 00:41:16,015
It's been great.

658
00:41:29,404 --> 00:41:31,698
(MOONLIGHT SERENADE PLAYING)

659
00:41:33,408 --> 00:41:35,243
Well! Hurry up, then!

660
00:41:47,422 --> 00:41:51,551
Okay, all right and turn.

661
00:41:54,554 --> 00:41:58,474
Okay, try and spin me again.
But this time, don't get my arm up my back.

662
00:41:58,599 --> 00:42:00,435
No extra points for a half-nelson.

663
00:42:00,560 --> 00:42:02,145
I'm sure I used
to know this stuff.

664
00:42:02,770 --> 00:42:03,813
Close the door, will you?

665
00:42:03,938 --> 00:42:06,649
Your ship's about to blow up,
there's gonna be a draft.

666
00:42:09,152 --> 00:42:11,112
Welcome to the Tardis.

667
00:42:11,779 --> 00:42:14,490
-Much bigger on the inside.
-You'd better be.

668
00:42:14,615 --> 00:42:18,161
I think what the Doctor is trying
to say is, you may cut in.

669
00:42:19,120 --> 00:42:21,956
-Rose! I've just remembered!
-What?

670
00:42:22,081 --> 00:42:24,042
(IN THE MOOD BY THE GLENN MILLER BAND)

671
00:42:24,125 --> 00:42:26,461
I can dance!

672
00:42:28,337 --> 00:42:32,341
Actually, Doctor,
I thought Jack might like this dance.

673
00:42:32,967 --> 00:42:36,137
I'm sure he would, Rose,
I'm absolutely certain.

674
00:42:36,929 --> 00:42:38,431
But who with?

675
00:43:09,796 --> 00:43:10,838
Whoo!

676
00:43:15,885 --> 00:43:18,513
And I was having
such a nice day.

677
00:43:19,138 --> 00:43:20,181
According to Intelligence,

678
00:43:20,306 --> 00:43:23,184
the target is the last surviving member
of the Slitheen family.

679
00:43:23,309 --> 00:43:25,853
A criminal sect from the planet
Rexicoricophalvitorius

680
00:43:26,020 --> 00:43:28,815
masquerading as a human being,
zipped inside a skin suit.

681
00:43:31,234 --> 00:43:34,529
Its nuclear power station right in
the heart of Cardiff city

682
00:43:34,654 --> 00:43:36,614
will bring jobs for all.

683
00:43:36,697 --> 00:43:39,033
And it just so happens to be
right on top of the rift.

684
00:43:39,200 --> 00:43:43,037
If this power station went into meltdown,
the entire planet would go...

685
00:43:45,373 --> 00:43:47,166
Go on then, run!

686
00:43:47,250 --> 00:43:49,544
It's the rift,
the rift's opening.

687
00:43:49,752 --> 00:43:51,546
The whole city's going to disappear!

688
00:43:51,671 --> 00:43:53,172
Time and space
are ripping apart.

689
00:43:53,256 --> 00:43:55,550
Never mind Cardiff,
it's going to rip open the planet!

